{"tid":1997721,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"大成功！路透社報導五一黃金週！請繼續爆買爆食黃店！","createTime":"2020-05-02T00:40:39.000Z","updateTime":"2020-05-02T08:56:30.000Z","uid":36592,"like":46,"dislike":0,"uniUserReply":19,"replies":[{"pid":"d506f41f856b4223094df23abf0e7fc083b5d84f","tid":1997721,"uid":36592,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-05-02T00:40:39.000Z","msg":"<strong><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"color: gold;\">LIKE + RETWEET<img src=\"/assets/faces/dog/bye.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/dog/bye.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/dog/bye.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /></span></span></strong><br />\n<a href=\"https://twitter.com/Reuters/status/1256237266881712128\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2FReuters%2Fstatus%2F1256237266881712128&d=29ui5Tvv6aczeWgqk0vw10YZmLIq74JPLN0FyuDKESI%3D&h=5f1e8865\" data-ef-url=\"https://embed.lih.kg/frame?u=https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2FReuters%2Fstatus%2F1256237266881712128&h=87a5a95d\" target=\"_blank\">https://twitter.com/Reuters/status/1256237266881712128</a><br />\n<br />\n以下節錄：<br />\n<strong><span style=\"color: gold;\">Business booms for 'yellow' firms backing Hong Kong protest movement</span></strong>（黃店刺激消費）<img src=\"/assets/faces/dog/bye.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><br />\n<br />\nHONG KONG (Reuters) - Hong Kong anti-government protesters queued outside businesses that openly support the democracy movement on Friday, a show of support for &ldquo;yellow&rdquo; restaurants and cafes reeling from the twin impact of the coronavirus crisis and months of demonstrations.<br />\n<br />\nWhile small businesses are bearing the brunt of the economic downturn in a city where rents are among the highest in the world, pro-democracy activists are providing a lifeline to so-called &ldquo;yellow&rdquo; companies, or those that back the movement.<br />\n<br />\n<span style=\"color: gold;\">Long lines formed at many restaurants and cafes, snaking out onto streets thanks to an online campaign dubbed &ldquo;Hongkonger&rsquo;s 5.1 Golden Week&rdquo; that called on people to visit yellow businesses over the long May Day weekend.（黃店大排長龍<img src=\"/assets/faces/pig/hehe.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />）</span><br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;This week is a great motivation for us to further strengthen the yellow economic circle. We need to keep resisting even though the crackdown is getting harder and harder,&rdquo; said Miki Chan, 25, who works in the education sector.<br />\n<br />\nThe &ldquo;yellow&rdquo; promotion comes at a time when mainland Chinese traditionally flock to the city, providing a boost to retailers. But most are staying at home due to travel restrictions adopted to curb the spread of the coronavirus.<br />\n<br />\n<span style=\"color: gold;\">Organisers said more than 2,300 businesses, including retailers, restaurants and wedding shops, joined the action and offered discounts to pro-democracy protesters.（超過2300商戶參與）<img src=\"/assets/faces/pig/dance.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /></span><br />\n<br />\nStepping up an economic campaign that took root amid sometimes violent protests last year, mobile apps and shop banners guided consumers to yellow businesses across the city.<br />\n<br />\nThe &ldquo;yellow economic circle&rdquo;, which contrasts with &ldquo;blue&rdquo; businesses, or those deemed pro-government, is seen as a way for people to support the protest movement through peaceful means.<br />\n<br />\nBUSTLING DISTRICT<br />\n<span style=\"color: gold;\">At Mainichi restaurant in the bustling working class district of Mong Kok, sales had plunged 70% since the outbreak of the coronavirus, but business was booming this week thanks to yellow circle promotions.</span>（武肺令生意大減，黃金週刺激消費<img src=\"/assets/faces/pig/dance2.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />）<br />\n<br />\nMary Ma, 25, who was dining at Mainichi&rsquo;s where colorful Post-it notes of support for the movement covered one wall, said it was a great way to maintain support.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;We might not be able to come out and protest every day due to the pandemic, but supporting yellow shops in our daily life is something everyone can do - it&rsquo;s a way to revolutionise our daily life,&rdquo; said Ma.<br />\n<br />\nMainichi&rsquo;s owner Chong, 35, formed a group called &ldquo;Small Mong Kok Alliance&rdquo; with yellow shops nearby and he offers his customers a yellow discount card to shop at members&rsquo; outlets.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;I have seen many young people come out and make sacrifices for Hong Kong&rsquo;s future. My restaurant is also part of the society, I want to make use of it to support the demands of the students. Their demands are also my demands,&rdquo; Chong said.<br />\n<br />\nKa Yung, 21, co-owner of a boutique shop called Freeland and also a member of the alliance, said she hoped to strengthen the circle by forming tie-ups with other yellow shops.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;No one can earn all the money himself. I would rather let shops with similar political views share the market than let the blue shops earn money,&rdquo; she said.<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-protests-mayday/business-booms-for-yellow-firms-backing-hong-kong-protest-movement-idUSKBN22D577\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Farticle%2Fus-hongkong-protests-mayday%2Fbusiness-booms-for-yellow-firms-backing-hong-kong-protest-movement-idUSKBN22D577&d=29ui5Tvv6aczeWgqk0vw10YZmLIq74JPLN0FyuDKESI%3D&h=de93e6bb\" data-ef-url=\"https://embed.lih.kg/frame?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Farticle%2Fus-hongkong-protests-mayday%2Fbusiness-booms-for-yellow-firms-backing-hong-kong-protest-movement-idUSKBN22D577&h=9a52aec5\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-protests-mayday/business-booms-for-yellow-firms-backing-hong-kong-protest-movement-idUSKBN22D577</a>"},{"pid":"5203a3d2bd882de39c3a0221f382cb452e32a9a6","tid":1997721,"uid":365